            <ObservedData>
              <Attribute Type="Description">In a girl, born of consanguineous Iranian parents (family 3), with neurodevelopmental disorder with hypotonia, facial dysmorphism, and brain abnormalities (NEDHFBA; 619383), Rehman et al. (2019) identified a homozygous 1-bp duplication (c.1607dupT, NM_001135629.2) in exon 16 of the PPP1R21 gene, resulting in a frameshift and premature termination (Leu536PhefsTer7). The mutation, which was found by exome sequencing and confirmed by Sanger sequencing, segregated with the disorder in the family. It was not present in public databases, including gnomAD. Fibroblasts derived from the patient in family 3 showed decreased PPP1R21 mRNA levels compared to controls. Unlike wildtype PPP1R21, mutant PPP1R21 failed to colocalize with the early endosome marker EEA1 (605070), suggesting that the variant is a null allele. In in vitro studies, patient fibroblasts showed delayed transferrin (190000) clearance and abnormal intracellular accumulation of myelin figures/myelin bodies compared to controls, suggesting endolysosomal dysfunction or a trafficking defect.</Attribute>
